, renown’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, kingdom’. <i>Rodrigo</i> is one of the most important Spanish personal names of ancient Germanic origin. It was borne by the last of the Visigoth kings and by a Christian saint, Saint Roderick, one of the 9th-century martyrs of Córdoba. This surname is also found in and around some of the former Portuguese territories of western India."]},{"name":"Ruis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Arturo, Carlos, Conception, Elba, Fernando, Jose, Josue, Juan, Jubenal, Lazaro, Lupe.","Spanish and Portuguese: variant of   Ruiz  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pedro","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Pedro Ruiz de Henestrosa was born in 1220, in Spain, his father, Ruy Martínez de Henestrosa, was 26 and his mother, Elvira Carrillo, was 22. He married María Ortiz de Zúñiga Rada in 1235, in Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Spain. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1252, in his hometown, at the age of 32."},"et":{"Cir 1220–1252":"1220–1252","1220–1252":"1220–1252","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1275–1358":"1275–1358","1241–Male":"1241–Surnud","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1248–1300":"1248–1300","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1194–1248":"1194–1248","1198–1223":"1198–1223","1198":"1198","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1241":"1241","Abt 1247":"umbes 1247","Cir 1220":"1220","1194":"1194","Abt 1241":"umbes 1241","1248":"1248","1358":"1358","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1300":"1300","Abt 1243":"umbes 1243","1243":"1243","Zúñiga, Zúñiga, Navarra, España":"Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Hispaania","Espano, Spain":"Hispaania","España":"Hispaania","Henestrosa, Spain":"Hispaania",",,, Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"Cir 1220–1252":"1220–1252","1220–1252":"1220–1252","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1275–1358":"1275–1358","1241–Male":"1241–Kuollut","1243–Female":"1243–Kuollut","1247–Female":"1247–Kuollut","1248–1300":"1248–1300","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1194–1248":"1194–1248","1198–1223":"1198–1223","1198":"1198","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1241":"1241","Abt 1247":"noin 1247","Cir 1220":"1220","1194":"1194","Abt 1241":"noin 1241","1248":"1248","1358":"1358","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1300":"1300","Abt 1243":"noin 1243","1243":"1243","Zúñiga, Zúñiga, Navarra, España":"Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Espanja","Espano, Spain":"E